column5: ['In the top 50', 'Between 51 and 60, inclusive', 'Between 61 and 75, inclusive', 'Above 75']
column6: ['Economic Indicators']
column11: This question was closed on option D ('Above 75') with a closing date of 28 September 2016. Iran ranked 76th in the 2016-2017 Global Competitiveness Index (World Economic Forum). In the World Economic Forum’s 2015-2016 Global Competitiveness Index, Iran ranked 74th among 140 countries (World Economic Forum 1, WEF 2). The reports are typically released in September. This question will be scored using the ordered categorial scoring rule. For more information, see the FAQ. Recommended Questions Will the government of Venezuela or Petroleos de Venezuela S. A. (PDVSA) default on their foreign-currency debt before 1 March 2016? Will the expanded Panama Canal open to shipping before 15 May 2016?

Changed my forecast to a 100% prediction for Iran's competitiveness to be ranked between 61 - 75 inclusive as there is no indication that it will have increased significantly from rank 74th in 2015. Iran’s rankings during 2012-14 were 66th, 82nd and 83rd respectively. However, the competitiveness of each country is based on 12 pillars. Iran has a lot going for it as it has a well educated workforce, diversified its sectors after the oil crash and has invested in science projects. However, the government's hesitation to open to foreign investors has also put a limit on growth potential and trading partners. Sources: https://www.bloomberg.com/quicktake/irans-economy http://www.cnbc.com/2016/05/19/how-oil-sanctions-may-have-helped-irans-economy.html

A recent piece in The Economist (US ed., Apr 23, pp 57-8; sorry--I still read things on paper, but this is progress, given that when I was your age it was all carved onto rocks) points out a couple of things which I knew but had sort of mislaid. The US embargo continues, along with sanctions that forbid anyone doing business in Iran from using the US financial system. OFAC has been either unwilling or unable to explain to the Iranians what they need to do to get this sorted, according to the piece. So (a) US firms can't do business in Iran, although businesses from other countries can do and have begun; and (b) financing arrangements for firms entering that market can be pretty convoluted, but at least they now exist. Whatever Iran does to try to get right with the US will be much more likely to enhance than to damage their competitiveness picture.

This questions depends a great deal on whether or not the increase in economic investments resulting from the lifting of nuclear sanctions will be reflected in this report or not until next year's report. The report is released in Sept and I contacted WEF to ask if the report was a forecast or an assessment of real time data. Here's their reply: "The Global Competitiveness Report assesses the current state of competitiveness of a country. It is based on hard data and on data from our Executive Opinion Survey. Should you want to know more about the Executive Opinion Survey, please see p. 75 of the report (http://www3.weforum.org/docs/gcr/2015-2016/Global_Competitiveness_Report_2015-2016.pdf )." Interestingly, the survey is conducted in 41 languages but Farsi is not one of them. As far as the nuclear deal implications, it seems to me that a report released in Sept based on surveys will take time to complete and teh surveys are probably going to end by late summer at latest. So I'm inclined to think much of the nuclear deal's outcomes will not be felt in GCI rankings until next year's report. And perhaps more importantly, here's a forecast of GCI for Iran in 2016 by quarter. It forecasts above 76 in each quarter: http://www.tradingeconomics.com/iran/competitiveness-rank/forecast http://www.tradingeconomics.com/iran/forecast

I looked at the changes in Global Competitiveness Index rank over the last 10 years, rank improved by more than 13 places in just 1.9% of the samples. My bias is that with sanctions being removed Iran's rank will improve. Of countries that improved their score, 3% improved by more than 13, and 97% were between -1 and 13. Iran is currently ranked at 74, moving into the 51-60 rank will require an improvement of 14 places, so small chance. No country has ever improved rank by more than 23 places, so moving to the top 50 isn't likely.
Improved from 83 the previous year and likely to improve further as sanctions are removed

Year-to-year, there is little change in a country's score. Even if reformers within Iran make huge gains, at least since the 2012-2013 index no country has risen over 14 places in the ranking in a single year, which Iran would have to do in order to rank in the top 60. As to whether it crosses below the 75th rank threshold, the average rank change for countries between 64 and 83 (a 20-rank range centered on 74; my way of approximating change in this section of the rankings) was 1.2 this year, 2 last year, and zero the year before that, so my prior is to assume a small positive change. Given that 5 of the 20 nations in the 64-83 range this year saw their ranking fall, as did 6 of 20 the year before, the average chance of dropping in rankings for a nation in this range is about 27.5%.

Based on the data in the 6 years since 2011-2012, Iran has gotten an average rank of 73, with a standard deviation of 8.5. If that describes Iran's rank this year, then the distribution should be <50: 0.4%, 51-60: 7%, 61-75: 54%, 75+: 39%. This is a reasonable "base rate" estimate for this question. The two big problems are: a) this sort of estimate almost certainly underestimates the chance of an extreme rank, so <50 and 51-60 should be larger b) The nuclear deal should be expected to push the average lower (because Iran becomes more competitive).

The outside view is the performance last year of 74. Among the 12 factors that they based their ranking, not many will change for Iran next year (investments in infrastructure will increase dramatically but budget problems with lower oil prices could hinder growth).

WEF has full dataset (since 2007) in their website, would be nice to do some fancy modelling of all averages and stuff, but can't afford the luxury. Looking instead in rankings only, just to see how common are big movements. Key facts. - Iran ranked 74-th in the last report, best position is 62 (2011-2012). - To fit into top 50, Iran must rank up by 24, next bin requires improvement by 14 positions. - There has been only one jump of 24+ positions in WEF dataset - Côte d'Ivoire improved its position to 91 from 115 in 2015. - 23 occasions in dataset where country has improved by 14+ positions. - There is no obvious pattern behind jumps, some of large improvements come after big drop, some enjoy high growth several years in a row. - No country has jumped into top-35, but there has been several big movements in/near top-50, e.g. Portugal 51>36 (2014), Kazakhstan 72>51 (2012), India 71>55 (2015).
